their personal mission?

717
00:35:48,146 --> 00:35:54,575
Dr. Kovac could have sent Mr. Ames
home with antibiotic pills, but he didn't.

718
00:35:54,786 --> 00:35:58,587
He assumed that Mr. Ames was
unreliable, that he couldn't be trusted...

719
00:35:59,724 --> 00:36:03,923
and so Dr. Kovac took
responsibility for his care.

720
00:36:04,095 --> 00:36:06,087
And then he abandoned
that responsibility...

721
00:36:06,297 --> 00:36:09,165
by subjecting Mr. Ames
to substandard conditions...

722
00:36:09,334 --> 00:36:14,068
in an understaffed ER where that man
was shoved into a corner and neglected.

723
00:36:14,239 --> 00:36:18,176
And the warning signs of a
major stroke were ignored...

724
00:36:18,343 --> 00:36:21,245
resulted in a
devastating disability.

725
00:36:21,579 --> 00:36:25,414
Before the stroke, Mr. Ames
was a skilled craftsman.

726
00:36:25,750 --> 00:36:28,219
He supported a
wife and two children.

727
00:36:28,386 --> 00:36:33,086
And now, with a paralyzed left arm, loss
of perception in his left visual field...

728
00:36:33,258 --> 00:36:36,524
that livelihood has
been taken away.

729
00:36:37,629 --> 00:36:43,967
Loss of income, loss of self-esteem,
has resulted in profound stress...

730
00:36:44,135 --> 00:36:48,266
and led to a divorce and
separation from his children.

731
00:36:48,440 --> 00:36:50,466
Mr. Ames now lives alone.

732
00:36:50,975 --> 00:36:54,571
He's trying to get by on a
disability benefit of $1300 a month.

733
00:36:55,246 --> 00:36:59,411
He cannot drive, he sees
his children one day a week...

734
00:36:59,584 --> 00:37:02,349
and he is being
treated for depression.

735
00:37:02,787 --> 00:37:06,121
Your award must fairly
compensate Mr. Ames...

736
00:37:06,291 --> 00:37:11,821
for past and ongoing medical
care, for 25 years of lost wages...

737
00:37:11,996 --> 00:37:14,295
and for the pain and
suffering that this man...

738
00:37:14,466 --> 00:37:18,403
will experience every
day for the rest of his life.

739
00:37:20,138 --> 00:37:23,336
And you wanna make sure that
this part rests against your rib cage...

740
00:37:23,508 --> 00:37:26,808
not your armpits,
and then... Oop.

741
00:37:26,978 --> 00:37:28,810
I'm okay. I'm okay.

742
00:37:28,980 --> 00:37:32,007
- You sure those things are safe?
- Yeah, they just need an adjustment.

743
00:37:32,183 --> 00:37:35,642
Or you can go to the
pharmacy and get a new pair.

744
00:37:35,820 --> 00:37:37,345
Good idea.

745
00:37:37,522 --> 00:37:39,013
Careful.

746
00:37:41,159 --> 00:37:43,151
Should we sign you
in as a trauma patient?

747
00:37:43,328 --> 00:37:45,126
I would say yes,
but my shift is over.

748
00:37:45,296 --> 00:37:47,595
Call me if your spleen ruptures.

749
00:37:48,333 --> 00:37:49,528
- Excuse me, hi.
- Hi.

750
00:37:49,701 --> 00:37:52,500
- Is Dr. Pratt around?
- He's with a patient. Can I help you?

751
00:37:52,670 --> 00:37:54,434
He told me he was
gonna be right back.

752
00:37:54,606 --> 00:37:56,472
Will you let him
know Chaz is waiting?

753
00:37:56,641 --> 00:37:57,665
Okay.

754
00:37:57,842 --> 00:38:00,937
- Hey, Neela, you have a minute?
- I have 12 hours. I'm on all night.

755
00:38:01,112 --> 00:38:03,013
- It's about Katey, your med student.
- Ray.

756
00:38:03,181 --> 00:38:04,945
Hey, hey, she asked
me out, all right?

757
00:38:05,116 --> 00:38:07,347
Residents are not allowed
to date their students.

758
00:38:07,519 --> 00:38:08,953
Not my student. Never will be.

759
00:38:09,120 --> 00:38:11,817
She's not doing an ER
elective, it's not against policy.

760
00:38:11,990 --> 00:38:13,618
Well, then, why even ask?

761
00:38:14,159 --> 00:38:16,628
Thanks. Appreciate your help.

762
00:38:17,295 --> 00:38:19,662
I'm sorry, I gotta go.

763
00:38:19,831 --> 00:38:21,322
- Tell Greg I'll call him.
- Okay.

764
00:38:21,499 --> 00:38:22,523
- Hey, Mayday.
- Hello.

765
00:38:22,700 --> 00:38:25,033
- What are you doing here?
- Small bowel obstruction.

766
00:38:25,203 --> 00:38:27,672
Good times. So, uh, how's
the guy who went up in flames?

767
00:38:27,839 --> 00:38:29,899
Minor partial burns to
the chest and abdomen.

768
00:38:30,074 --> 00:38:32,873
You know, I hear
his aorta was just fine.

769
00:38:33,044 --> 00:38:36,378
There's a lesson to be learned
here. Wise men say only fools rush in...

770
00:38:36,548 --> 00:38:38,073
Oh, you missed
a guy called Chaz.

771
00:38:38,249 --> 00:38:39,717
He left?

772
00:38:40,051 --> 00:38:41,713
You were saying?

773
00:38:44,355 --> 00:38:46,517
Hey, Chaz, Chaz, hold up, man.

774
00:38:46,691 --> 00:38:48,922
Sorry about that. I got
caught up with a patient.

775
00:38:49,093 --> 00:38:50,994
It's okay. I gotta go.

776
00:38:51,162 --> 00:38:53,393
Now, come on, man.
Sounded like something serious.

777
00:38:53,565 --> 00:38:56,160
- It's all good.
- Hey.

778
00:38:58,069 --> 00:39:00,595
Things are just not
going so well at home.

779
00:39:00,772 --> 00:39:02,206
Really?

780
00:39:02,373 --> 00:39:04,069
When I wanna
study, it's too noisy.

781
00:39:04,242 --> 00:39:06,711
When I wanna bring my
friends over, Dad won't let me.

782
00:39:06,878 --> 00:39:09,575
I'm always late to class because
the commute takes forever.

783
00:39:09,747 --> 00:39:11,079
What about the dorm?

784
00:39:11,249 --> 00:39:12,717
Costs too much.

785
00:39:12,884 --> 00:39:15,353
When you saw me earlier, I
was looking for apartments.

786
00:39:15,520 --> 00:39:18,490
But they all kind of sucked.

787
00:39:19,023 --> 00:39:21,219
Look, I know this is
gonna sound crazy...

788
00:39:21,392 --> 00:39:26,228
but I was thinking, maybe I
could move into your place.

789
00:39:28,433 --> 00:39:29,457
My place?

790
00:39:29,634 --> 00:39:33,093
Yeah, your place. I
mean, it's close to campus.

791
00:39:33,271 --> 00:39:35,934
I can get a part-time job
to help you with the rent.

792
00:39:36,107 --> 00:39:39,077
I'm quiet. We'll probably
never even see each other.

793
00:39:39,244 --> 00:39:40,303
You're serious?

794
00:39:42,113 --> 00:39:45,641
Ah, Chaz, come on, man.
You know, I got my own style.

795
00:39:45,817 --> 00:39:47,581
Oh, come on.

796
00:39:47,752 --> 00:39:50,620
You say the word, and
I'm gonna clear out for you.

797
00:39:51,256 --> 00:39:56,627
And if it doesn't work out,
I'll be gone real fast, man.

798
00:40:01,933 --> 00:40:03,424
Never mind, it's a bad idea.

799
00:40:03,801 --> 00:40:06,168
All right, look...

800
00:40:07,572 --> 00:40:09,404
Let's try it for a month.

801
00:40:10,275 --> 00:40:11,299
For real?

802
00:40:12,610 --> 00:40:15,136
Yeah, I'll talk to your mom.

803
00:40:15,446 --> 00:40:16,470
- Thank you.
- All right.

804
00:40:16,648 --> 00:40:18,139
Thank you.

805
00:40:18,917 --> 00:40:22,046
- I'm gonna holler at you.
- All right, man, take it easy.

806
00:40:25,623 --> 00:40:27,615
- Hey. Ha-ha-ha.
- Yeah.

807
00:40:27,792 --> 00:40:29,488
So, uh, how was
the first day back?

808
00:40:29,661 --> 00:40:32,529
It was a piece of
cake. Like riding a bike.

809
00:40:32,697 --> 00:40:34,325
Oh, yeah? You
miss your little man?

810
00:40:34,499 --> 00:40:36,092
Yeah, but that's okay.

811
00:40:36,267 --> 00:40:38,498
I'll bond with him again
when I feed him at 11...

812
00:40:38,670 --> 00:40:41,162
and 2 and 5 a.m.

813
00:40:41,472 --> 00:40:43,373
But you know what
was nice about today?

814
00:40:43,574 --> 00:40:47,136
For 12 hours, I talked like
a grownup to grownups.

815
00:40:47,312 --> 00:40:49,838
Well, except for when you
had to deal with the surgeons.

816
00:40:50,014 --> 00:40:51,949
Yeah, at least they
don't spit up on you.

817
00:40:52,116 --> 00:40:53,584
Much.

818
00:40:54,185 --> 00:40:55,517
Good night.

819
00:40:55,687 --> 00:40:56,985
Try to get some rest.

820
00:40:57,155 --> 00:40:59,181
It's a nice idea.

821
00:41:01,025 --> 00:41:02,891
How long do you
think they'll deliberate?

822
00:41:03,094 --> 00:41:05,495
Shouldn't take more
than a day or two.

823
00:41:05,663 --> 00:41:08,326
Ames' lawyer is
a publicity hound.

824
00:41:08,499 --> 00:41:12,163
The local news is having
a field day trashing County.

825
00:41:12,337 --> 00:41:16,172
It'd be good to get you in front of the
press as the doctor found not guilty.

826
00:41:16,341 --> 00:41:18,003
Well, you are very optimistic.

827
00:41:18,176 --> 00:41:20,338
People need to hear
our side of the story...

828
00:41:20,511 --> 00:41:24,209
to reassure them that the
County health system works.

829
00:41:25,183 --> 00:41:29,985
During that videotape, did you
see the looks on the jury's faces?

830
00:41:30,355 --> 00:41:33,655
Doctors get sued for ignoring
and undertreating patients...

831
00:41:33,825 --> 00:41:35,657
not for doing too much.

832
00:41:36,861 --> 00:41:38,853
Plus, you did a
great job on the stand.

833
00:41:39,030 --> 00:41:40,396
I don't think so.

834
00:41:42,066 --> 00:41:44,194
I've been to at least
a hundred trials.

835
00:41:44,369 --> 00:41:46,838
I can tell when a
jury likes the doctor.

836
00:41:49,540 --> 00:41:52,908
He's just another greedy MD
getting rich by overtreating.

837
00:41:53,077 --> 00:41:55,672
- What are you talking about?
- I've read about it.

838
00:41:55,847 --> 00:41:59,841
The drug companies give kickbacks to
doctors who use their expensive drugs.

839
00:42:00,585 --> 00:42:03,020
The judge instructed us
not to decide this case...

840
00:42:03,187 --> 00:42:05,053
based on anything
we've heard outside.

841
00:42:05,223 --> 00:42:08,625
<i>They neglected this
guy for three days.</i>

842
00:42:08,793 --> 00:42:10,284
<i>His pneumonia was improving.</i>

843
00:42:10,461 --> 00:42:13,522
<i>That doctor used a hand
grenade to kill a mosquito.</i>

844
00:42:13,698 --> 00:42:16,099
<i>To me, that's bad
medical judgment.</i>

845
00:42:16,267 --> 00:42:17,428
<i>You're not a doctor.</i>

846
00:42:17,602 --> 00:42:20,538
<i>We've got to decide this based
on the expert witness definition...</i>

847
00:42:20,705 --> 00:42:21,934
<i>of the standard of care.</i>

848
00:42:22,106 --> 00:42:24,439
<i>Well, when you're talking
about County General...</i>

849
00:42:24,609 --> 00:42:26,441
<i>the term "standard
of care" is a joke.</i>

850
00:42:26,611 --> 00:42:28,910
<i>That's right. Kovac
is part of the system.</i>

851
00:42:29,781 --> 00:42:32,808
<i>And we all know
the system sucks.</i>
